// Neural Networks and Learned Molecular Representations
// =============================================================================

=== Neural Networks and Learned Molecular Representations <nn-learned-repr>

The application of neural networks to molecular property prediction dates to the early 1990s, when multilayer perceptrons were first coupled with hand-engineered molecular descriptors for quantitative structure--property relationship modeling. Zupan and Gasteiger's 1993 textbook provided an accessible introduction that catalyzed adoption across chemical subdisciplines @Zupan1993Neural. Around the same period, Baskin, Palyulin, and Zefirov proposed a neural architecture that bypassed explicit descriptor computation altogether, feeding graph-derived atom-level features directly into a network whose topology enforced invariance to atom renumbering @Baskin1997Neural. These early efforts demonstrated that even shallow networks could rival or surpass linear regression when the descriptor space was sufficiently rich, but they were fundamentally limited by two constraints: the quality and completeness of the hand-crafted descriptor sets, and the modest dataset sizes typical of experimental chemistry.

A conceptual breakthrough arrived when researchers began allowing the neural network itself to learn molecular representations end-to-end, rather than relying on fixed fingerprints such as Extended-Connectivity Fingerprints. Lusci, Pollastri, and Baldi pioneered this direction by applying recursive neural networks to undirected molecular graphs for aqueous solubility prediction, demonstrating that learned representations could outperform hand-crafted descriptors on standard benchmarks @Lusci2013Deep. Duvenaud et al. extended this idea more generally with their "neural fingerprint" model, which replaced each layer of the circular fingerprint algorithm with a differentiable neural network layer operating on the molecular graph @Duvenaud2015Convolutional. This work was significant not merely for its predictive accuracy but for demonstrating that circular fingerprints were a special case of a broader, learnable family of molecular representations. Concurrently, Ramsundar et al. introduced massively multitask networks for drug discovery, training a single deep network on more than 200 biological activity datasets simultaneously and showing that shared representations across tasks improved prediction on individual endpoints @Ramsundar2015Massively. This was an early and influential demonstration of multi-task learning for molecular properties.

Kearnes et al. formalized the notion of molecular graph convolutions, introducing learnable edge features alongside node features and benchmarking the resulting architecture across diverse molecular property prediction tasks @Kearnes2016Molecular. Their work highlighted that operating on the full molecular graph, rather than on a fixed-radius fingerprint, allowed the network to capture long-range intramolecular interactions more naturally. The conceptual landscape was then unified by Gilmer et al., who proposed the Message Passing Neural Network (MPNN) framework @Gilmer2017Neural. The MPNN framework abstracted earlier graph-based models---including Duvenaud's neural fingerprints and Kearnes's graph convolutions---into a common formalism consisting of a message function, an update function, and a readout function. Applied to the QM9 quantum chemistry benchmark, MPNNs achieved state-of-the-art results on 11 of 13 target properties. This framework became the de facto reference architecture for molecular graph neural networks, and its vocabulary---message passing, aggregation, readout---pervades the field to this day.

Sch\"utt et al. developed SchNet, which introduced continuous-filter convolutional layers that operate on atomic positions in three-dimensional space rather than on a discrete bond graph @Schutt2018SchNet. By modeling interatomic distances with radial basis functions and learning filters in continuous space, SchNet could capture spatial interactions at arbitrary resolution, making it particularly effective for predicting quantum-mechanical properties of molecules and materials. Around the same time, Wu et al. released MoleculeNet, a standardized benchmark suite for molecular machine learning encompassing quantum mechanics, physical chemistry, biophysics, and physiology datasets @Wu2018MoleculeNet. MoleculeNet was distributed as part of the DeepChem open-source framework, which provided reference implementations of featurization pipelines and model architectures, establishing a common evaluation infrastructure that has shaped the field's trajectory.

// =============================================================================
// Graph Neural Networks: Expressiveness, Attention, and Geometry
// =============================================================================

=== Graph Neural Networks for Molecular Graphs <gnn-molecular>

The year 2019 saw a rapid diversification of GNN architectures addressing distinct limitations of the original GCN and MPNN designs. Kipf and Welling's Graph Convolutional Network (GCN) had established a spectral-inspired convolutional operation on graph-structured data, where each node aggregates information from its immediate neighbors via a normalized adjacency matrix @Kipf2017Semi. Though originally designed for citation networks, the GCN framework was quickly adopted for molecular graphs, where atoms serve as nodes and bonds as edges with atomic properties encoded as node features.

Xu et al. introduced the Graph Isomorphism Network (GIN), motivated by a theoretical analysis showing that standard GNNs are at most as powerful as the Weisfeiler--Leman graph isomorphism test in distinguishing non-isomorphic graphs @Xu2019How. GIN achieves maximal discriminative power within this bound by using a sum aggregator with learnable injective functions, making it provably as expressive as the 1-WL test. This work established a critical theoretical benchmark for GNN expressiveness that continues to shape the field, and Morris et al. extended the analysis to higher-order $k$-WL hierarchies @Morris2019Weisfeiler. In the domain of molecular fingerprints, Xiong et al. proposed AttentiveFP, which applies a graph attention mechanism to learn molecular representations directly from 2D molecular graphs @Xiong2020Pushing. AttentiveFP uses atom-level and molecule-level attention layers that weight the contributions of neighboring atoms according to learned relevance scores, enabling interpretable identification of substructures important for a given property. The model achieved state-of-the-art results across multiple MoleculeNet tasks including solubility, lipophilicity, and toxicity endpoints.

Also in 2019, Yang et al. introduced the Directed Message Passing Neural Network (D-MPNN), implemented in the Chemprop software package @Yang2019. Unlike standard MPNNs that pass messages between atoms, D-MPNN associates messages with directed edges, which prevents so-called "totters"---redundant message paths of the form $v_1 arrow v_2 arrow v_1$---that dilute information flow. Benchmarked across 19 public and 16 proprietary datasets, D-MPNN consistently matched or exceeded competing architectures and random-forest baselines with molecular fingerprints, establishing Chemprop as one of the most widely adopted GNN tools in cheminformatics. Heid et al. subsequently released an updated Chemprop package extending D-MPNN with support for multi-molecule systems, reaction property prediction, uncertainty quantification, and transfer learning workflows @Heid2024Chemprop.

Gasteiger et al. introduced DimeNet (Directional Message Passing for Molecular Graphs), which incorporates 3D geometric information---specifically interatomic distances and bond angles---into the message passing framework @Gasteiger2020Directional. By embedding messages between atom pairs and transforming them based on angular information, DimeNet captures directional interactions that are invisible to purely topological 2D GNNs, achieving substantial improvements on molecular energy and force prediction tasks. DimeNet and its faster successor DimeNet++ demonstrated that encoding 3D structure is essential for quantum-chemical property prediction, though at the cost of requiring 3D conformer generation as a preprocessing step. Hu et al. extended the benchmarking effort with the Open Graph Benchmark, which includes molecular datasets derived from MoleculeNet but with more rigorous scaffold-based splits and a leaderboard infrastructure that has driven rapid progress @Hu2020Open.

Despite their success, GNNs face several well-characterized limitations. The over-smoothing problem causes node representations to converge to indistinguishable states as the number of message-passing layers increases, effectively limiting GNN depth and the size of molecular neighborhoods that can be captured. The related phenomenon of over-squashing compresses information from exponentially growing receptive fields into fixed-size vectors, losing long-range dependencies. Wieder et al. catalogued over 80 GNN variants applied to more than 20 molecular properties across 48 datasets, confirming the breadth of GNN adoption while highlighting these persistent challenges @Wieder2020Compact. For thermophysical property prediction specifically, the requirement for large, high-quality training data remains a bottleneck: viscosity and surface tension datasets are orders of magnitude smaller than the drug-discovery datasets on which most GNN architectures were developed. Additionally, temperature and pressure dependence---critical for thermophysical applications---requires either multi-task formulations or auxiliary input features, as standard molecular GNNs encode only molecular structure and not thermodynamic state variables.

