=== Transformers and Self-Supervised Pretraining <transformers-pretraining>

The success of the Transformer architecture in natural language processing prompted researchers to investigate whether molecular strings could be treated as a chemical "language." Schwaller et al. provided an early and influential demonstration with the Molecular Transformer, which cast chemical reaction prediction as a sequence-to-sequence translation problem over SMILES strings, achieving over 90% top-1 accuracy on standard benchmarks without requiring hand-crafted atom mappings @Schwaller2019MolecularTransformer. Honda et al. introduced the SMILES Transformer, which used unsupervised encoder--decoder pretraining on a large SMILES corpus to learn continuous molecular fingerprints @Honda2020SMILESTransformer. This work showed that pretrained representations outperformed rule-based fingerprints and graph methods specifically in low-data regimes, a finding directly relevant to property prediction tasks with limited labeled compounds.

The bidirectional masked language modeling paradigm pioneered by BERT was quickly adapted for chemistry. Fabian et al. proposed MolBERT, which combined masked SMILES token prediction with domain-relevant auxiliary tasks such as molecular descriptor regression, demonstrating that injecting chemical knowledge during pretraining improved downstream virtual screening and QSAR performance even with a relatively modest four-million-compound pretraining set @Fabian2020MolBERT. Chithrananda et al. released ChemBERTa, adapting the RoBERTa architecture to 77 million PubChem SMILES with purely self-supervised masked language modeling, showing that performance scaled predictably with pretraining corpus size @Chithrananda2020ChemBERTa. Ahmad et al. extended this line with ChemBERTa-2, systematically comparing masked language modeling against multi-task supervised pretraining and establishing that multi-task pretraining on computed descriptors yielded the most transferable representations @Ahmad2022ChemBERTa2. Beyond token-level masking, contrastive self-supervised methods emerged as a complementary strategy. Wang et al. introduced MolCLR, which operates on molecular graphs rather than SMILES strings, applying stochastic augmentations---atom masking, bond deletion, subgraph removal---and training a GNN encoder with a contrastive objective that pulls augmented views of the same molecule together while pushing different molecules apart @Wang2022MolCLR.

A parallel thread addressed a fundamental limitation of SMILES-based models: the SMILES string is a linearization of molecular topology and discards explicit 3D spatial information. Ying et al. introduced Graphormer, a Transformer architecture for graph-structured data that encodes structural information through centrality encoding, spatial encoding based on shortest-path distances, and edge feature encoding in the attention mechanism @Ying2021Graphormer. Graphormer won first place in the OGB-LSC quantum property prediction challenge and demonstrated that standard Transformer attention, when properly augmented with graph-structural biases, can outperform specialized message-passing GNNs. Rampasek et al. generalized this direction with the GPS (General, Powerful, Scalable) framework, which decouples local message-passing from global Transformer attention, achieving linear complexity in the number of nodes and edges while matching or exceeding Graphormer's performance across 16 benchmarks @Rampasek2022GPS. Moving further toward physical realism, Zhou et al. proposed Uni-Mol, a universal 3D molecular pretraining framework that directly takes atomic 3D coordinates as input using an SE(3)-equivariant Transformer backbone @Zhou2023UniMol. Pretrained on 209 million molecular conformations with masked atom prediction and 3D position denoising tasks, Uni-Mol outperformed prior state-of-the-art on 14 of 15 molecular property prediction benchmarks, confirming that 3D geometric information provides substantial gains over 1D or 2D representations alone.

=== Transfer Learning for Small Datasets <transfer-small-datasets>

A persistent challenge in molecular property prediction is label scarcity: experimental measurements are expensive, and many target properties have only hundreds or low thousands of data points. Hu et al. systematically addressed this by evaluating strategies for pretraining graph neural networks @Hu2020Strategies. They showed that naive node-level or graph-level pretraining could lead to negative transfer, but a combined strategy---pretraining at both levels using self-supervised objectives on large unlabeled molecular corpora, followed by fine-tuning on the target task---yielded up to 9.4% absolute improvement in ROC-AUC on molecular property benchmarks. This work established pretraining as a viable strategy for molecular GNNs and stimulated a wave of follow-up research on self-supervised molecular representation learning.

These developments have collectively pushed the field toward chemical foundation models: large pretrained architectures intended to serve as general-purpose molecular encoders @Fang2025FoundationModelsPerspective. The central value proposition is that self-supervised pretraining on millions of unlabeled structures learns transferable chemical representations that can be fine-tuned with far fewer labeled examples, directly addressing the data scarcity that characterizes most experimental property prediction tasks. For a problem such as the one considered in this report, where fewer than 1,000 compounds have matched NMR spectra and thermophysical measurements, the pretrain-then-fine-tune paradigm is especially compelling: the model can learn general molecular syntax, substructure patterns, and conformational preferences from vast unlabeled corpora, then adapt to the specific NMR-to-property mapping with the limited labeled data available.

However, significant limitations remain. SMILES-based models are sensitive to tokenization choices and SMILES canonicalization. Graph Transformers require careful positional encoding design to capture the structural information that message-passing GNNs handle naturally. 3D pretraining methods such as Uni-Mol depend on the quality of conformer generation, which introduces noise for flexible molecules. Recent analyses have noted that foundation models for chemistry still struggle with out-of-distribution generalization and that the benefits of scale plateau when downstream tasks involve property types---such as bulk thermophysical properties---that are poorly represented in pretraining objectives focused on quantum-level or pharmacological endpoints @Fang2025FoundationModelsPerspective. For thermophysical applications specifically, GNN and Transformer models have been applied to viscosity prediction by Chew et al. @Chew2024 and to surface tension of polymers by Tamnanloo et al. @Tamnanloo2025Surface, but both studies found that incorporating physics-based features or domain-specific descriptors substantially improved predictions beyond what end-to-end learned representations achieved alone. These considerations motivate hybrid approaches that combine experimentally grounded spectroscopic descriptors with learned representations rather than relying solely on pretrained models.
